                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Photographs of Whitman County, Washington, 1892-1921.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Materials consist of photographs, newspaper clippings, invitations, and a poster of Colfax, dating from 1892-1921. Original prints taken between 1892-1898 record campus life at Washington State University including scenes of students, the administration and mechanical buildings, the Science Building, the "Crib", the Ferry Hall file of 1897, military cadets, class portraits, class picnics, athletic activities, and the hanging of General Wyler's effigy during the Spanish War. There are also scenes from the Barkhuff homestead near Colton and views of Pullman and Colfax. The bulk of the material concerns the late 1800's. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                  <abstract>The Herbert M. Parker Foundation, along with Washington State University, supported a project to obtain oral histories from former employees, involved with health physics and radiation protection, of the Hanford Nuclear Reservation. Two student interns were hired to manage this process. Each interviewee was recorded on audio and/or video taped by the interns. Following each interview, biographies on each interviewee were comprised of notes from the interview. Interviewees include: George Backman, Bill Baumgartner, Fred Cross, George W.R. Soldat, Madge Watson, Robert Wilson, Jerry Yesberger. </abstract>
                  <name>

                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>

                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Records, 1908-1967, bulk 1915-1950.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Series I consists of correspondence, reports, contest summaries, newspaper clippings, some memorabilia, lists, photographs, and performance records. Intercollegiate sports included in the series are badminton, baseball, basketball, boxing, fencing, football, golf, handball, lacrosse, riding, skiing, swimming, tennis, track, weightlifting, and wrestling. Series II contains correspondence, some photographs, greeting cards and includes numerous examples of military letterheads for the period. Series III contains the early correspondence, minutes, and rules of the conference during its formative period. Series IV is a loose association of class notes, annual reports, budgets, functional reports, and administrative reference materials that clearly do not give a complete picture of the function of that department. Series V (motion picture films) deal with ski jumping and football. Series VI (Score Books) record specific athletic performances in baseball, basketball, wrestling, softball and interscholastic track but are primarily baseball and basketball. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Gaines and McCullough family papers, 1902-2008.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>This collection includes papers of Edward F. and Xerpha Mae McCulloch Gaines consisting of letters between them, correspondence with their children, other correspondence, newspaper clippings, photographs, research notes for both Edward and Xerpha, a few professional papers, and some genealogical information. Of note in E.F. Gaines's "letter box" (subseries 2.4) is his correspondence with pioneers in plant genetics, many with State College of Washington (WSC) connections. Other items of interest include the courtship letters from Edward to Xerpha. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                  </name>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Historical Photograph Collections.</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Photographs of Washington State University and Pullman, 1927-1973.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>In 1983, this collection of some 1,600 prints was selected from the entire Hutchinson Studio donation of 122 boxes of negatives. The collection is arranged according to subject with dates provided when known. The photographs record the changes on the campus of WSU and in rural communities of the Palouse region of southeastern Washington and northern Idaho between the 1920s and the 1970s. Agricultural photographs trace the shift from the use of horses in harvesting to modern combines. Neighboring geographic areas are also represented. These include the Columbia River gorge, the heavily forested areas of northeastern Idaho and the semi-arid deserts of central Washington. In addition to the campus of WSU and wheat farming, there are scenes of pea processing, logging, shipping, and construction. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Barbara J. Sibley student activism collection, 1969-1973.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>The items in this collection consist of newspaper clippings, special publications, and other documents pertaining to student activism on the Washington State University campus, circa 1970. The printed articles in this collection come from various newspapers, including the Pullman Herald and the Daily Evergreen, as well as other periodicals, and include descriptions and images pertaining to student activism, especially on the Washington State University campus. Other printed materials in the collection include publications of the Racism Workshop Committee, as well as flyers and public notices by various student and faculty groups, such as the Strike Steering Committee, Black Student Union (BSU) and Chicano Student Movement (MECHA). Many of the articles and documents highlight specific incidents related to the 1970 student strikes and racism on and around the campus of Washington State University. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: Barbara J. Sibley student activism collection, 1969-1973.
resource.abstract: The items in this collection consist of newspaper clippings, special publications, and other documents pertaining to student activism on the Washington State University campus, circa 1970. The printed articles in this collection come from various newspapers, including the Pullman Herald and the Daily Evergreen, as well as other periodicals, and include descriptions and images pertaining to student activism, especially on the Washington State University campus. Other printed materials in the collection include publications of the Racism Workshop Committee, as well as flyers and public notices by various student and faculty groups, such as the Strike Steering Committee, Black Student Union (BSU) and Chicano Student Movement (MECHA). Many of the articles and documents highlight specific incidents related to the 1970 student strikes and racism on and around the campus of Washington State University.

<objectXMLWrap>
               <mods xmlns="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3">
                  <recordInfo>
                     <recordOrigin>WorldCat:768250527</recordOrigin>
                     <recordContentSource>ISIL:OCLC-NTE</recordContentSource>
                  </recordInfo>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Army Specialized Training Reserve Program, United States Army (ASTRP Company A, Unit 3923) collection, 1944-2007.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>This collection consists of materials related to ASTRP Company A, Unit 3923, mainly from the years following their military service. It documents the sustained long-term relationships of many members, and the group's post-war activities. Most of the records are those kept by member Hector Garcia as the informal archivist for the group, and the balance includes papers from Bob Glotzbach, a member who authored a history of the cohort, Fortunate Soldiers (or Soldiers of Fortune) (Glen Ellen, CA: Regeneration Sources, 1997).  The materials include correspondence, company rosters, files related to Garcia's efforts to locate cohort members, reunion files, statistical reports and compilations, collected historical materials, photographs and audiovisual media.  The collection is named in honor of Hector Garcia (1926-2009). </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Papers, 1945-1994.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>The Ronald Keith Sorem Papers contain extensive material on deep-sea mining research for manganese nodules, basic research by Ronald K. Sorem on the composition and formation of manganese nodules, and information on organizations promoting and funding this research. There is also information about his career as a geology professor at Washington State University including material about his classes and about the geology department. Also contained is material about the Marine Mineral Resources Museum at the University, which he was instrumental in founding. There are general files regarding research expeditions Dr. Sorem was on, grant proposals and consulting projects, and information on his book "Manganese Nodules," 1979. Other files pertain to his work with the National Science Foundation, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, and there are files documenting his work for the United States Geological Survey in the Philippine Islands, and on the Domes Project and the United States Exclusive Economic Zone Symposium. As a member of the International Association on the Genesis of Ore Deposits and an officer of its Commission on Manganese, there is information on that association's symposium and its participation in other international mining congresses. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>University of Wyoming, American Heritage Center</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

Also contained is material about the Marine Mineral Resources Museum at the University, which he was instrumental in founding. There are general files regarding research expeditions Dr. Sorem was on, grant proposals and consulting projects, and information on his book "Manganese Nodules," 1979. Other files pertain to his work with the National Science Foundation, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, and there are files documenting his work for the United States Geological Survey in the Philippine Islands, and on the Domes Project and the United States Exclusive Economic Zone Symposium.                   <unitdate>1927-1973</unitdate>
                  <physdesc>
                     <extent>2 containers.</extent>
                     <extent>1600 items.</extent>
                  </physdesc>
                  <abstract>In 1983, this collection of some 1,600
		  prints was selected from the entire Hutchinson Studio donation of 122 boxes of
		  negatives. The collection is arranged according to subject with dates provided
		  when known. The photographs record the changes on the campus of WSU and in
		  rural communities of the Palouse region of southeastern Washington and northern
		  Idaho between the 1920s and the 1970s. Agricultural photographs trace the shift
		  from the use of horses in harvesting to modern combines. Neighboring geographic
		  areas are also represented. These include the Columbia River gorge, the heavily
		  forested areas of northeastern Idaho and the semi-arid deserts of central
		  Washington. In addition to the campus of WSU and wheat farming, there are
		  scenes of pea processing, logging, shipping, and construction.</abstract>
                  <langmaterial>Collection materials are in
		  <language>English</language>
                  </langmaterial>
               </did>
            </objectXMLWrap>

Agricultural photographs trace the shift  from the use of horses in harvesting to modern combines. Neighboring geographic  areas are also represented.                   </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Washington State University photographs, 1948-1983. 1948-1983</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>This collection comprises the former print and negative file (from the department of Printing, later the Office of University Publications and Printing/WSU Press) of official campus photographs including Bob Bullis, and Norm Nelson, covering academic and extra-curricular activities at Washington State University. The images record a wide range of events, people, and places around the WSU campus. Sporting Events, ROTC ceremonies, and portraits of faculty, figure prominently in the photographs. This present collection is divided roughly in half with photographic prints mounted on WSU press file cards and their corresponding negatives housed separately. The following index is arranged by subject in alphabetical order with a navigation table present at the top and bottom of each section. To the right of each entry is the date and the photograph number. Please note that a small number of entries in this guide refer to prints and/or negatives that are no longer present in the collection. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Washington State University</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

                     <corpname>
                        <subarea>Music Division</subarea> Library of Congress</corpname>
                     <address>
                        <addressline>Washington, D.C.</addressline>
                     </address>
                  </repository>
                  <abstract>Collection contains materials collected by Slonimsky throughout his lifetime that document his life and work as musicologist, composer, conductor, lecturer and author. Included are personal biographical materials; Slonimsky's writings (drafts, typescripts, reprints, etc.) of newspaper, periodical, journal, and magazine articles, record liner notes, radio broadcasts, and talks, published and unpublished; music composed by Slonimsky, manuscript and printed; concert programs; correspondence, among many others, with Henry Cowell, Alexandre Gretchaninoff, Roy Harris, Charles Ives, and Edgar Varèse; biographical materials on composers and performers mosly generated when Slonimsky was editing Baker's and The international cyclopedia; music collected by Slonimsky, manuscript and printed and multi-composer collections; among the manuscripts are many short holographic works and fragments; scrapbooks; and iconographical material, such as family photographs an those of composers and musicians from the former Soviet Union, as well as little known musicians from the United States and elsewhere.</abstract>
               </did>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: Nicolas Slonimsky Collection 1873-1997 (bulk 1920-1990)
resource.abstract: Collection contains materials collected by Slonimsky throughout his lifetime that document his life and work as musicologist, composer, conductor, lecturer and author.                      <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Roger "Rod" Davidson interviews, 2002 June 27 and Sept. 20.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Davidson discusses his experience working as a smokejumper in Idaho during the summers of 1947 through 1950. During the winters he attended both Washington State University and the University of Idaho where he obtained his degree in 1950. Davidson then attended the American Institute for Foreign Trade in Phoenix, Ariz. The training he received from that institution landed him a job with Mobil Oil Company in southern California. In 1963 he transferred to Boise, Idaho. While he was employed with Mobil Oil, he was also co-owner and accountant for the Brass Lamp Pizza parlors. In the 1960s and 1970s, Davidson bought property for the Brass Lamp Pizza parlors. He also bought property in McCall and Boise, including a building at 6th and Main in Boise. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Idaho State Historical Society Library & Archives</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: Roger "Rod" Davidson interviews, 2002 June 27 and Sept. 20.
resource.abstract: Davidson discusses his experience working as a smokejumper in Idaho during the summers of 1947 through 1950. During the winters he attended both Washington State University and the University of Idaho where he obtained his degree in 1950. Davidson then attended the American Institute for Foreign Trade in Phoenix, Ariz. The training he received from that institution landed him a job with Mobil Oil Company in southern California. In 1963 he transferred to Boise, Idaho. While he was employed with Mobil Oil, he was also co-owner and accountant for the Brass Lamp Pizza parlors. In the 1960s and 1970s, Davidson bought property for the Brass Lamp Pizza parlors. He also bought property in McCall and Boise, including a building at 6th and Main in Boise.

                  <unittitle>William Delbert
		  Barkhuff Photographs</unittitle>
                  <unitdate>1892-1921 </unitdate>
                  <physdesc>
                     <extent>1 container.</extent>
                     <extent>.5 linear feet of shelf space.</extent>
                     <extent>270 items.</extent>
                  </physdesc>
                  <abstract>Materials consist of photographs,
		  newspaper clippings, invitations, and a poster of Colfax, dating from
		  1892-1921. Original prints taken between 1892-1898 record campus life at
		  Washington State University including scenes of students, the administration
		  and mechanical buildings, the Science Building, the "Crib", the Ferry Hall file
		  of 1897, military cadets, class portraits, class picnics, athletic activities,
		  and the hanging of General Wyler's effigy during the Spanish War. There are
		  also scenes from the Barkhuff homestead near Colton and views of Pullman and
		  Colfax. The bulk of the material concerns the late 1800's.</abstract>
                  <langmaterial>Collection materials are in
		  <language>English</language>
                  </langmaterial>
               </did>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: William Delbert  Barkhuff Photographs 1892-1921
resource.abstract: Materials consist of photographs,  newspaper clippings, invitations, and a poster of Colfax, dating from  1892-1921. Original prints taken between 1892-1898 record campus life at  Washington State University including scenes of students, the administration  and mechanical buildings, the Science Building, the "Crib", the Ferry Hall file  of 1897, military cadets, class portraits, class picnics, athletic activities,  and the hanging of General Wyler's effigy during the Spanish War. There are  also scenes from the Barkhuff homestead near Colton and views of Pullman and  Colfax. The bulk of the material concerns the late 1800's.
